[normal]Q1 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] Thank you very much for coming in to see us this afternoon. Do not feel obliged, all th
[normal]ree of you, to answer all questions
[normal] but
[normal] please do chip in
[normal] if you have something that is demonstrably different from what one
[normal] of your colleagues has said
[normal]. What do you think the bank had in mind when they created forward guidance? I will go to Mr Larsen, Mr Wood and then Mr Wells.
[normal]Jens Larsen[bold]: I think the bank had it in 
[normal]mind to reduce uncertainty. It was not quite to reduce uncertainty in the way that the market or perhaps the public expected it, which is to reduce the uncertainty unconditionally about where interest rates were going, but to reduce the uncertainty about their reaction function, to make people understand the circumstances in which they would change monetary policy. I think a great deal of the disappointment in 
[normal]the 
[normal]markets reflects that. They were expecting a more unconditional statement, a clearer commitment of some kind, whereas th
[normal]e committee’s aim was 
[normal]more to clarify the circumstances surrounding an eventual rate hike.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]Robert Wood[bold]: 
[normal]I pretty much agree with that. I think guidance more or less describes what the bank was already doing, which is trying to support the economy as much as possible.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q2 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] That would mean loosening policy.
[normal]Robert Wood[bold]: Yes, and I think the unemployment rate they have given is a bit more certainty about how they see the economy and where they want to head to, s
[normal]o it was aiming at giving 
[normal]more transparenc
[normal]y and 
[normal]certainty about, in the jargon, their reaction function or how they would behave.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q3 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] T
[normal]o be clear, when you say 
[normal]“
[normal]s
[normal]upport 
[normal]the economy as much as possible
[normal]”
[normal], 
[normal]do 
[normal]you mean support the economy more than it had been supported by the monetary p
[normal]olicy as explained hitherto?
[normal]Robert Wood[bold]: If you are asking me if I thought it was a loosening of policy, my answer would be yes, a little bit. In answer to the initial question you asked, I think it w
[normal]as extra transparency and 
[normal]more certainty about its goals and what it was aiming for.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q4 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] Yes, but one of t
[normal]he things it was aiming for—indeed, a crucial purpose—was 
[normal]to loose
[normal]n policy. That is what you 
[normal]effectively said.
[normal]Robert Wood[bold]: I think it did loosen policy a little bit, yes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q5 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] Therefore
[normal] it has fulfilled its purpos
[normal]e, or is fulfilling its purpose?
[normal]Robert Wood[bold]: Yes, 
[normal]I guess you could say that.
