[normal]Q6 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] Mr Wells?
[normal]Simon Wells[bold]: The others have covered the s
[normal]tated aims quite well. T
[normal]here is another unstated aim we hav
[normal]e to look at. If
[normal] we rewind to the beginning of the year, we were still talking about triple dip recessions in the 
[normal]UK
[normal], the economy looked like it was heading for another tough year, and there was some reasonable demand from people and politicians for the Bank of England to do something, when there was not an awful lot left in its toolkit. I think the forward guidance we saw was in some sense a necessary response to some of the pressure that they were under at that time.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q7 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] That is an explanation for 
[normal]how we got to where we are. 
[normal]I think there is one dis
[normal]senter from the three of you to
[normal] this
[normal],
[normal] on the basis of what you have said so far. This did loosen policy a bit, it did increase transparency a little, and it has increased certainty a little. Is there any disagreement? I think there is a bit of disagreement from Mr Larsen on the last. 
[normal]Jens Larsen[bold]: As
[normal] with
[normal] every statement that has to do with forward guidance, it is a conditional statement. I have learned more about the bank’s reaction function, but I have sat down and thought very hard about it and constructed my own unemployment 
[normal]forecast
[normal] 
[normal]and studied the documents very careful
[normal]ly. T
[normal]here is a slightly different perception
[normal] among the people I speak to in the market
[normal], which is that this has no
[normal]t reduced uncertainty and
[normal] has created 
[normal]more confusion about what 
[normal]the bank is trying to do 
[normal]and how this is meant to work
[normal]—
[normal]for instance, how the status 
[normal]of the bank
[normal]’s inflation forecast 
[normal]has changed, whether the unemployment threshold is a threshold or a trigger, and so 
[normal]on. There are many dimensions of this policy that 
[normal]I can just about keep in my head, but I do spend a lot of time thinking about it.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q8 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] You seem to be saying 
[normal]something rather different
[normal] there
[normal], which is that this is extreme
[normal]ly complex, sophisticated stuff
[normal] and that any reaction people might have had is probably from ignorance.
[normal]Jens Larsen[bold]: I would not say it is extremely complicated and I would not say
[normal] it is ignorance. W
[normal]hen the bank has tried to set out in
[normal] words what it is trying to do—
[normal]which is effectively saying that this recovery is likely to be different and that it wants to keep rates low until it has come to the point where you have strong growth for a while, where employment has increased, unless 
[normal]they see a risk to inflation or 
[normal]there is a financial stability risk—I think those words are quite clear. I am less sure that the threshold and the three knockouts add much to cl
[normal]arity. I changed my mind on that
[normal]. I thought in advance that this might be a good idea with the specific t
[normal]hresholds and 
[normal]knockouts, 
[normal]but it has turned out 
[normal]that these have been misunderstood.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q9 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] Yes. Y
[normal]ou seemed to be saying a moment ago that they were decreasing certainty, adding to uncertainty.
[normal]Jens Larsen[bold]: Taking the unemployment threshold as an example, if you put out a numerical and very precise threshold, 7%, and you publish a forecast, you should expect people
[normal] to look very carefully at that
[normal] forecast and interpret th
[normal]e 7% as something very
[normal] specific. I think most markets have a perception tha
[normal]t that is, if not exactly, 
[normal]certainly so
[normal]mething very close to a trigger
[normal] where mone
[normal]tary policy is likely to be tightened
[normal]. The MPC has since been very clear in emphasising that 
[normal]it is not a trigger but
[normal] a chance to r
[normal]e-evaluate monetary policy. I
[normal]t is a chance to think again about the inflation forecast at the point at which unemployment is 7%. 
[normal]I think that rather diminishes the clarity and importance of the 7% threshold
[normal] and the mar
[normal]ket is focusing much more on w
[normal]hen i
[normal]s unemployment going to hit 7%.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q10 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] I am trying to summarise that again. Yo
[normal]u are saying that it is complex
[normal] and that they have
[normal] therefore 
[normal]reduced certainty. That is what I said a moment ago.
[normal]Jens Larsen[bold]: I agree, yes. I t
[normal]hink it is complex and 
[normal]the straightforward formulation of forward guidance is much more helpful.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q11 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] Is it more complex in reducing certainty, Mr Wood and Mr Wells?
[normal]Robert Wood[bold]: 
[normal]I pretty much agree with what Jens said. It is a complicated way of saying something pretty simple, which was where I started out, which is, “We think the economy can grow pretty quickly over the next few years. We are going to do all we can to support that by keeping interest rates low, and we are going to do that until we see some strong growth, unemployment coming down and the economy looking better”. The
[normal]re is a simple message in there
[normal] but the imple
[normal]mentation of it has been 
[normal]complicated. The executive summary in the document runs to three p
[normal]ages, which I think is a 
[normal]complicated way of saying something you could probably put in one sentence.
[normal]Simon Wells[bold]: I agree with the others. In a way, what the Bank of England is trying to say is, “This time it is different. This time we will see strong data, strong demand, and economic supply will respond as well, so there will be less inflationary pressures”. I think the problem is that message is not getting through to the market. The market is saying, “This time it is not different. We are going to see strong data, we are going to see strong demand, and then you are going to tighten policy”. The top level message is quite simple, but operationalising it has proved quite complicated for them.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q12 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] I know others may come on to this more in a moment. Do you think it has made the first tightening more difficult because it is focusing so much attention now on the detailed triggers for this that we run a greate
[normal]r risk than we might have done of what appears to have happened in America, where just talking about tapering the extremely loose policy generated a flurry of concern in the markets?
[normal]Simon Wells[bold]: With any new and unorthodox policy, the further you go down that route, th
[normal]e harder exit
[normal] is. I think forward guidance has been yet another step to try to keep monetary conditions as loose as possible for as long as possible, and in that sense it certainly complicates exit. More generally, by putting this simple message out—which is that despite the recovery, interest rates are going to stay lower for longer—of course, if the Bank of England’s
[normal] forecasts turn out to be wrong and
[normal] all of our forecasts 
[normal]turn out to be wrong, then 
[normal]the element of surprise to any eventual tightening is going to be greater. 
[normal]Jens Larsen[bold]: M
[normal]easuring it in terms of uncertainty or volatility about interest rates, this policy will lead to
[normal] volatility around the point at
[normal] which we are getting close to the threshold. Indeed, that is why the bank, as Charlie Bean said yesterday, is likely to have to do some more forward guidance at that point, either by lowering the unemployment threshold or by giving some other shape of forward guidance. 
[normal]There is more in
[normal] the
[normal] pipeline.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q13 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] In other word
[normal]s, 
[normal]we have to generate more of this complexity and uncertainty in order to reduce the risk of even greater complexity and uncertainty at the time of exit. That is what you have just said.
[normal]Jens Larsen[bold]: I think that is right, yes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q14 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] That does not sound like a ringing endorsement of this policy.
[normal]Jens Larsen[bold]: I do not think it is a ringing—
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q15 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] 
[normal]But you 
[normal]began quite enthusiastic
[normal]ally
[normal], Mr Larsen.
[normal]Jens Larsen[bold]: I would not say I am overly enthusiastic. It is a difficult policy. The exit in any case is going to be a very difficult point to administer, and I think more communication is likely to be needed. Whether they had done forward guidance or not, that exit would have been a tricky one. At the moment there is a very simple message on the exit strategy, which is about raising rates and then selling assets subsequently, but when it comes to it, guidin
[normal]g expectations about the path for
[normal] interest rates and asset sales at that point will be very difficult indeed, forward guidance or not.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q16 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] Is anybody disagreeing with that, before I move on?
[normal]Robert Wood[bold]: No. I would just add that exiting from a long period of very low interest rates would have been hard either way. If they had not given us an unemployment threshold, we would probably have been speculating about what it was. We have one now, so there is going to be a lot of focus on passing that particular number, and no doubt we will see more guidance as we get to it. Either way, it would have been pretty difficult, and as we approached a period where rates would probably have had to go up, the
[normal]n we would have had
[normal] the speculation anyway.
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] We are only looking here today at the difference between forward guidance and not forward guidance, whic
[normal]h was the pre-existing policy, s
[normal]o we are talking about the additional help or hindrance that we get from t
[normal]hat policy to exit.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q17 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark Garnier:[bold] It sounds less like forward guidance and more like 
[normal]forward obfuscation, doesn’t it
[normal]?
[normal]Jens Larsen[bold]: That mig
[normal]ht be a little unkind. I 
[normal]think the history here matte
[normal]rs, as Simon said earlier. 
[normal]Mark Car
[normal]ney started talking about nominal
[normal] GDP targeting 
[normal]back in December of last year. W
